Feature: lead-architect template grounds the BC @scenario_hash pre-state enumeration in the lead-held features/ surface and mailbox-reported register, not a clone grep

  Supersedes scenario 92 (features/templates/92-lead-architect-pre-state-verification-enumerates-bc-scenario-hash-set-on-retire-supersede-contradict.gherkin). The Implementer must locate the BC-side hash of scenario 92 in the shopsystem-templates feature surface and retire that hash when landing this scenario.

  Scenario 92 directed the architect to enumerate the BC's pinned @scenario_hash set "from the BC's 'features/' directory rather than from the lead shop's scenario register." Per ADR-018 D1, there is no repos/<bc> clone on the lead host, so a BC-side features/ directory is not a surface the lead can enumerate. The discipline survives — the architect must still establish the conflicting @scenario_hash set before composing a dispatch that retires, supersedes, or contradicts prior BC-side coverage — but its source-of-truth re-grounds to the contract/artifact surface: the lead-held "features/" Gherkin in this repo, the scenario hashes computed via the installed "scenarios hash" CLI (ADR-018 D2), and the BC's mailbox-reported scenario register/hashes carried in its "work_done" demonstration. This scenario re-grounds the pin accordingly.

  Scenario: lead-architect template's pre-state discipline directs the architect to enumerate the conflicting BC @scenario_hash set from the lead-held features/ surface and the mailbox-reported register whenever a dispatch retires, supersedes, or contradicts prior BC-side coverage
    When I read the lead-architect template via "shop-templates show lead-architect"
    Then the content names "@scenario_hash" as a pre-state surface the architect must enumerate before composing a dispatch that retires, supersedes, or contradicts prior BC-side coverage
    And the content directs the architect to establish that @scenario_hash set from the lead-held "features/" Gherkin in this repo together with the BC's mailbox-reported scenario register/hashes, and not from a "repos/<bc>" clone
    And the content names invoking the installed "scenarios hash" contract tool over the lead-held scenario text as the means of computing the hashes for that enumeration
    And the content marks the enumeration as a discrete pre-state step (alongside the contract-surface behavior-verification step), not as optional guidance the architect may skip
    And the content names at least one of the trigger conditions "retire", "supersede", or "contradict" as the gate that requires the enumeration step
